Here is a perfect example on how to swaddle your newborn! ✨The @embebabies starter swaddle is for babies 0-3 months, and includes adjustable lengths to grow with your baby. Ensure you are always swaddling 3 inches below the shoulders, and wrapping nice and snug. 
Any swaddling questions?! Comment below, and tag a mama who needs one!❤️

node.title: How to Swaddle Your Baby (0-3 months)

node.text:
"I don’t feel like myself. I told my husband after the first couple weeks being home with a newborn(my first experience with Harlem). Something just felt off & I was struggling to sort through my emotions & explain how I truly was feeling. I tried everything within me to not name what I was going through as postpartum depression. I had so much to be grateful for. Yet, deep down, I was dealing with these waves that would come crashing. From straight excitement, to then feeling as though I was failing. It wouldn’t always show up in the form of tears or sadness, but in anger & resentment. Days that felt like this dark cloud would linger over me & cause me to doubt my ability as a mother.
⠀
As I was walking through this new season of motherhood for the first time, I really didn’t know what to expect. I know my midwives talked about Postpartum depression, but I didn’t think I would be someone who would struggle with it. I was strong mentally I would tell myself. I was fighting everything within me to control these wild thoughts about myself & baby.
⠀
I made every excuse because I felt ashamed. In between sleep deprivation & the imbalance of chemicals in my brain, I didn’t even realize I was in the thick of things until after. When I could finally see the light at the end of the tunnel, I felt so much relief. I didn’t seek help medically, although I probably should have.
⠀
So mama, if you are walking through this season, please understand this is normal. So many women are going through this, yet not enough women are talking about it due to fear of feeling like they aren’t a good mama. Everyone experiences postpartum differently & that’s okay. There’s no shame in seeking help. It does get better & you will begin to feel like yourself again. Sending you so much love from one mama to another. 🧡"
📸: @sopharush

node.text:
“I was worried my heart wouldn’t be able to love another child as much as I do Kai. With Kai, it was love at first sight. It wasn’t that I didn’t love Kenzo but his newness was a bit disarming. My initial recovery after Kenzo’s birth was also more taxing than with Kai’s. Kai was all I knew for almost four years. And then all of a sudden there’s a new baby, equally mine yet somehow unfamiliar.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I felt weirdly guilty being with him those first few days in hospital and not with Kai. As if I was having a strange parental affair. Then Kai met Kenzo and gave me his ‘approval’ (him jumping up and down counts as approval). I studied Kenzo’s face, we snuggled, we made more eye contact when he got out of that sleepy first days stage and my heart seemingly out of nowhere absorbed him. It’s like he had always been there, just not in physical form.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Turns out, my heart was holding space for Kenzo all this time.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
How did you transition to your new child? Did you bond straight away or did it take some time?"⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

📷: @aishaandlife

node.text: What an incredible day! We have an amazing team here at Embé, and it was the first time a few of us met in person (even after working together for years!) It took a lot of planning and teamwork but we had a fantastic shoot today! We’re so excited to show you what we’ve been working on🤍

node.text:
“It’s been 5 weeks and I can still FEEL this picture.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
After 36 hours of labour - he was in my arms. While everyone around me was cleaning and doing paperwork, time stood still as I fed him for the first time. The adrenaline was wearing off, the epidural was losing its effect and my whole body was dead weight. I was the most exhausted I’d ever been in my entire life - and it was so worth it.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I asked my husband to take lots of pictures this time around. I wanted to remember every moment. The good, the bad, the excitement, the pain and everything else that comes with child birth. It all happens so quickly - in the grand scheme of things. You spend 9 months growing a human and within days or sometimes hours - you’ve gone through the entire birth process. With all of the emotions that come along with birth - the hormones, adrenaline, fear, chaos - it’s easy to forget and appreciate what your body just did.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It’s easy to forget the special moments like this.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I didn’t know he had taken this picture.. and the first time I saw it, I felt so overwhelmed with emotion. It brought me right back to that moment. One that I probably would have forgotten all about."⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

📷 @terriannmichelle
